SECTION 177. Failure To File The Required Answer. - A respondent principal/employer or Overseas Filipino Worker subject of a pending complaint for disciplinary action who fails to submit to the jurisdiction of the POEA shall be disqualified from participating in the overseas employment program until the respondent files an Answer.

SECTION 178. Automatic Disqualification of Principal/Employer. - The principal/employer shall be automatically included in the list of disqualified principal/employer without further proceedings if a final and executory judgment issued by the NLRC against the principal/employer is not satisfied. An Order to this effect shall be issued by the Administrator. Certified true copies of the Order and sheriff's return indicating failure to satisfy the judgment must be furnished to the Administration.

SECTION 179. Lifting of the Automatic Disqualification. - The automatic disqualification shall be lifted upon full satisfaction of the judgment award, evidenced by certified true copies of the sheriff's return indicating full compliance by the principal/employer.

SECTION 180. Temporary Disqualification of Principal/Employer and Overseas Filipino Worker. - A principal/employer who refuses to honor the medical result of a DOH-accredited medical clinic shall be temporarily disqualified from the overseas employment program. An Overseas Filipino Worker against whom a Warrant of Arrest or Hold Departure Order was issued by a competent authority shall be disqualified unless cleared by the Administration.

SECTION 181. Effect of Disqualification of Principal/Employer. - The principal/employer penalized with disqualification is barred from participating in the overseas employment program unless cleared or penalty lifted. An Order of permanent disqualification and delisting is immediately executory pending appeal.

SECTION 182. Grant of Clemency to a Principal/Employer. - The Administration may grant clemency upon motion if:
- a. The respondent is a first time offender;
- b. The respondent did not commit a serious offense;
- c. Claims against respondent have been settled;
- d. The offended party has pardoned the respondent;
- e. The principal/employer can provide decent employment for OFWs.
Filing a Motion for Clemency waives the right to appeal or withdraws a pending appeal.

SECTION 183. Grant of Clemency to an Overseas Filipino Worker. - Clemency may be granted if:
- a. The offense is not serious or does not involve moral turpitude, misrepresentation or theft;
- b. There is a settlement of claims or complainant has condoned the acts.

SECTION 184. Grant of Clemency to a Partner, Officer, or Director of a Cancelled Licensed Recruitment Agency. - Clemency may be granted if:
- a. The agency has only one case involving not more than ten workers for which license was cancelled;
- b. The officer/director did not participate in the violation;
- c. Proof of full satisfaction of awards;
- d. Complainants condoned the acts;
- e. The person has not participated in overseas employment program for at least four years since license cancellation;
- f. Submission of NBI clearance;
- g. Proof of publication of intent to apply for re-admission.
Grant of clemency under this section may be availed only once.
